Consider the following solution to the producer-consumer problem using a buffer of size 1. Assume that the initial value of count is 0. Also assume that the testing of count and assignment to count are atomic operations.

Producer:
Repeat
  Produce an item;
  if count = 1 then sleep;
  place item in buffer;
  count = 1;
  Wakeup(Consumer);
Forever

Consumer:
Repeat
  if count = 0 then sleep;
  Remove item from buffer;
  count = 0;
  Wakeup(Producer);
  Consume item;
Forever

Show that in this solution it is possible that both the processes are sleeping at the same time.

A. Yes, both processes can sleep simultaneously due to a race condition
B. No, the atomic test-and-assign prevents both from sleeping
C. Only the producer can sleep
D. Only the consumer can sleep

Fill in the boxes below to get a solution for the reader-writer problem, using a single binary semaphore, mutex (initialized to 1) and busy waiting. The solution uses variables: int readcount = 0; semaphore mutex = 1;

Reader:
L1: wait(mutex);
    readcount = readcount + 1;
    if (readcount == 1) then wait(mutex);  [Box 1]
    signal(mutex);
    do the read;
    wait(mutex);
    readcount = readcount - 1;
    if (readcount == 0) then signal(mutex); [Box 2]
    signal(mutex);

Writer:
L2: wait(mutex);  [Box 3]
    do the write;
    signal(mutex);

b. Can the above solution lead to starvation of writers?

A. Box 1: wait(mutex); Box 2: signal(mutex); Box 3: wait(mutex); starvation of writers is possible
B. Box 1: signal(mutex); Box 2: signal(mutex); Box 3: wait(mutex); starvation is not possible
C. Box 1: wait(mutex); Box 2: wait(mutex); Box 3: signal(mutex); starvation is not possible
D. Box 1: signal(mutex); Box 2: wait(mutex); Box 3: signal(mutex); starvation of writers is possible
